ame for a fisherman or fish seller, or a nickname for someone supposedly resembling a fish in some way, from Old Norse <i>fiskr</i> ‘fish’ (cognate with Old English <i>fisc</i>). See   Fish   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Fiske","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from a farm in western Norway, named from Old Norse <i>fiskr</i> ‘fish’ + <i>-e</i> from <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’.","English (East Anglia): variant of   Fisk  ."]},{"name":"Fish","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>fish</i>, <i>fisch</i>, <i>fisk</i> ‘fish’ (Old English <i>fisc</i>, Old Norse <i>fiskr</i>), a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman or fish seller, or a nickname for someone thought to resemble a fish.","Americanized form of German   Fisch  , and a variant of the same Jewish (Ashkenazic) surname. The surname of Jewish and German origin is also found in Britain.","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Poisson   ‘fish’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Fisk was born in 1435, in Laxfield, Suffolk, England, his father, Symon Fiske, was 39 and his mother, Susanna Smyth, was 34. He had at least 1 daughter with Joan Lynne. He died in 1504, in his hometown, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1435–1504":"1435–1504","1425–1504":"1425–1504","1427–1495":"1427–1495","1428–1491":"1428–1491","1432–Female":"1432–Surnud","1437–1504":"1437–1504","1427–1504":"1427–1504","1455–1559":"1455–1559","1397–1464":"1397–1464","1402–1433":"1402–1433","1495":"1495","1491":"1491","1437":"1437","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1424":"1424","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1432":"1432","1464":"1464","1397":"1397","26 February 1464":"26. veebruar 1464","1428":"1428","1504":"1504","1559":"1559","1427":"1427","Shotley, Suffolk, England":"Shotley, Suffolk, England","Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Laxfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Laxfield, Suffolk, England":"Laxfield, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1435–1504":"1435–1504","1425–1504":"1425–1504","1427–1495":"1427–1495","1428–1491":"1428–1491","1432–Female":"1432–Kuollut","1437–1504":"1437–1504","1427–1504":"1427–1504","1455–1559":"1455–1559","1397–1464":"1397–1464","1402–1433":"1402–1433","1495":"1495","1491":"1491","1437":"1437","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1424":"1424","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1432":"1432","1464":"1464","1397":"1397","26 February 1464":"26. helmikuuta 1464","1428":"1428","1504":"1504","1559":"1559","1427":"1427","Shotley, Suffolk, England":"Shotley, Suffolk, England","Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Laxfield, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Laxfield, Suffolk, England":"Laxfield, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1435–1504":"1435–1504","1425–15